1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,662
You are walking down a sidewalk when a police officer stops you, turns you
around, and runs

2
00:00:06,662 --> 00:00:13,324
his hands along the outside of your clothes. He has no warrant. He has not
seen you commit

3
00:00:13,324 --> 00:00:19,986
a crime . Most people assume that is illegal. It is not. The rule that allows
it was written

4
00:00:19,986 --> 00:00:26,648
in 1968, and it began with one detective watching two men pace in front of a
store window .

5
00:00:26,648 --> 00:00:33,310
This is the case that drew the line between a hunch and proof.

6
00:00:33,310 --> 00:00:39,378
We think of the Fourth Amendment as a simple wall: the police need a warrant,
or at least solid

7
00:00:39,378 --> 00:00:45,446
evidence, before they can search you. For most of American history, that was
close to true.

8
00:00:45,446 --> 00:00:51,514
But there is a gap in that wall, and almost every street stop in the country
now passes through

9
00:00:51,514 --> 00:00:57,582
it . Over the next twelve minutes: the ordinary afternoon that created the
gap, the standard

10
00:00:57,582 --> 00:01:03,650
the Supreme Court invented to fill it, and the quiet cost of letting suspicion
— not proof

11
00:01:03,650 --> 00:01:09,718
— put a hand on your shoulder.

12
00:01:09,718 --> 00:01:13,849
It is October 1963, in downtown Cleveland, Ohio. A plainclothes detective
named Martin McFadden,

13
00:01:13,849 --> 00:01:17,980
thirty-nine years on the force, is watching the street the way he has watched
it for decades

14
00:01:17,980 --> 00:01:22,112
.

15
00:01:22,112 --> 00:01:28,309
He notices two men. One walks down the block, pauses at a particular store
window, looks inside,

16
00:01:28,309 --> 00:01:34,506
and walks on. A short distance away he turns, comes back, and looks into the
same window again.

17
00:01:34,506 --> 00:01:40,703
Then the second man does exactly the same thing. Back and forth, the two of
them, about a dozen

18
00:01:40,703 --> 00:01:46,900
trips in all — five or six times apiece .

19
00:01:46,900 --> 00:01:52,226
To most people on the sidewalk, this is nothing. To McFadden, it is a pattern
he recognizes.

20
00:01:52,226 --> 00:01:57,552
Men do not usually study a single store window a dozen times in the middle of
the afternoon.

21
00:01:57,552 --> 00:02:02,877
He believes he is watching two men case a robbery — checking the layout, the
register, the

22
00:02:02,877 --> 00:02:08,203
way out .

23
00:02:08,203 --> 00:02:13,109
He has not seen a crime. He cannot point to stolen goods or a weapon in plain
view. What he

24
00:02:13,109 --> 00:02:18,015
has is experience and a strong suspicion. Under the ordinary rule, that is not
enough to search

25
00:02:18,015 --> 00:02:22,921
anyone.

26
00:02:22,921 --> 00:02:28,731
McFadden approaches the men, identifies himself, and asks for their names.
They mumble a reply.

27
00:02:28,731 --> 00:02:34,541
And now he has a decision to make. If these men are about to rob a store, at
least one of them

28
00:02:34,541 --> 00:02:40,350
may be carrying a gun. If he is wrong, he is about to put his hands on
innocent people for

29
00:02:40,350 --> 00:02:46,160
no legal reason.

30
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:51,195
He spins one of the men, John Terry, around and pats the outside of his coat.
He feels the

31
00:02:51,195 --> 00:02:56,231
shape of a pistol. He reaches in and takes it out. A second pistol comes off
the other man

32
00:02:56,231 --> 00:03:01,266
.

33
00:03:01,266 --> 00:03:05,914
Terry is charged with carrying a concealed weapon . And his case exposes a
problem the law

34
00:03:05,914 --> 00:03:10,561
had been avoiding for a long time.

35
00:03:10,561 --> 00:03:16,500
The Fourth Amendment protects people against "unreasonable searches and
seizures." By 1963,

36
00:03:16,500 --> 00:03:22,439
the usual test for a search was demanding: an officer needed probable cause —
a fair, fact-based

37
00:03:22,439 --> 00:03:28,378
belief that a specific crime had been committed — and often a warrant signed
by a judge.

38
00:03:28,378 --> 00:03:33,510
Detective McFadden had none of that. He had not watched a robbery happen. He
had watched two

39
00:03:33,510 --> 00:03:38,642
men look in a window. If the court measured his pat-down against the full
probable-cause standard,

40
00:03:38,642 --> 00:03:43,774
the gun was an illegal search, and under the rule from our last episodes, the
evidence would

41
00:03:43,774 --> 00:03:48,906
be thrown out.

42
00:03:48,906 --> 00:03:55,490
But push the other way, and a different danger appears. Police officers
approach suspicious

43
00:03:55,490 --> 00:04:02,075
people every day, long before a crime is complete. If an officer can never
check a person for

44
00:04:02,075 --> 00:04:08,659
a weapon until he already has proof of a crime, then the most dangerous moment
of the job —

45
00:04:08,659 --> 00:04:15,244
the unknown person, the unseen gun — is also the moment the law leaves him
most exposed.

46
00:04:15,244 --> 00:04:21,441
So the question that reached the Supreme Court was narrow and uncomfortable.
Is there a kind

47
00:04:21,441 --> 00:04:27,638
of police contact that sits below a full arrest — a brief stop, a quick check
for weapons —

48
00:04:27,638 --> 00:04:33,835
that the Constitution should allow on less than probable cause? Or does
opening that door hand

49
00:04:33,835 --> 00:04:40,032
the police a tool they will use on anyone, for almost any reason?

50
00:04:40,032 --> 00:04:46,359
The Court understood both sides of that question. It knew the streets were
real, and so was

51
00:04:46,359 --> 00:04:52,685
the temptation to abuse a softer rule. The decision it wrote in 1968 tried to
hold both truths

52
00:04:52,685 --> 00:04:59,011
at once, and that is exactly why it has been argued about ever since.

53
00:04:59,011 --> 00:05:05,886
In 1968, by a vote of eight to one, the Supreme Court upheld the search . The
opinion was written

54
00:05:05,886 --> 00:05:12,761
by Chief Justice Earl Warren — the same Court that, in these same years, was
expanding the

55
00:05:12,761 --> 00:05:19,636
rights of suspects across the country . That detail matters. This was not a
Court looking for

56
00:05:19,636 --> 00:05:26,511
ways to help the police. It was a Court that decided the street was a genuine
exception.

57
00:05:26,511 --> 00:05:32,224
The Court built its answer in two parts. First, the stop. An officer may
briefly stop a person

58
00:05:32,224 --> 00:05:37,937
when he can point to specific, describable facts that make him reasonably
suspect that crime

59
00:05:37,937 --> 00:05:43,650
is afoot . Not a hunch he cannot explain — facts he can lay out later, the way
McFadden could

60
00:05:43,650 --> 00:05:49,363
describe the pacing and the window.

61
00:05:49,363 --> 00:05:56,024
That phrase — specific and articulable facts — is doing quiet, heavy work. It
means an officer

62
00:05:56,024 --> 00:06:02,686
cannot simply say a person looked suspicious and leave it there. He has to be
able to name

63
00:06:02,686 --> 00:06:09,348
what he saw and explain why it added up. McFadden could: two men, the same
window, a dozen

64
00:06:09,348 --> 00:06:16,010
trips, their heads together between each pass. Reasonable suspicion is not a
feeling the officer

65
00:06:16,010 --> 00:06:22,672
has; it is a story he can tell afterward, in specific terms, that a judge can
test .

66
00:06:22,672 --> 00:06:28,288
Second, the frisk. If, during that stop, the officer reasonably believes the
person may be

67
00:06:28,288 --> 00:06:33,904
armed and dangerous, he may run his hands over the outer clothing — and only
the outer clothing

68
00:06:33,904 --> 00:06:39,520
— to check for weapons . The purpose is narrow: not to find evidence, but to
make sure no one

69
00:06:39,520 --> 00:06:45,137
gets shot during the encounter.

70
00:06:45,137 --> 00:06:50,946
And the Court drew that limit tightly. A frisk is not a license to empty your
pockets. It is

71
00:06:50,946 --> 00:06:56,756
a pat-down of the outer clothing, feeling for the hard shape of a weapon —
nothing more. If

72
00:06:56,756 --> 00:07:02,566
an officer goes further, reaching in to explore for something that is plainly
not a weapon,

73
00:07:02,566 --> 00:07:08,376
he has crossed the line the Court drew and stepped back into the world that
needs probable

74
00:07:08,376 --> 00:07:14,186
cause and a warrant . The whole point was to give an officer just enough, and
not one inch

75
00:07:14,186 --> 00:07:19,995
more.

76
00:07:19,995 --> 00:07:26,386
The Court was honest about what this was. A stop is a seizure. A frisk is a
search . It did

77
00:07:26,386 --> 00:07:32,777
not pretend otherwise. It simply held that this limited kind of search could
be reasonable

78
00:07:32,777 --> 00:07:39,168
on a lower standard than probable cause — a new standard the law now calls
reasonable suspicion

79
00:07:39,168 --> 00:07:45,559
. With that, the gun found on Terry was allowed to stand .

80
00:07:45,559 --> 00:07:51,213
One justice refused to go along. William O. Douglas warned that the Court was
giving an officer

81
00:07:51,213 --> 00:07:56,868
on the street a power that even a judge did not have — the power to seize and
search a person

82
00:07:56,868 --> 00:08:02,523
without probable cause. To loosen the rule below probable cause, he wrote, was
a long step

83
00:08:02,523 --> 00:08:08,178
down a dangerous road . His was the single dissenting voice. But it would echo
for the next

84
00:08:08,178 --> 00:08:13,833
half-century.

85
00:08:13,833 --> 00:08:18,739
The "Terry stop" became one of the most common encounters between police and
the public in

86
00:08:18,739 --> 00:08:23,645
America . Every day, officers stop people on a standard that is real but
blurry: facts that

87
00:08:23,645 --> 00:08:28,551
add up to reasonable suspicion.

88
00:08:28,551 --> 00:08:34,167
The strength of the rule is also its weakness. "Reasonable suspicion" depends
on judgment,

89
00:08:34,167 --> 00:08:39,783
and judgment can be sharpened by training — or bent by bias. In the decades
after Terry, some

90
00:08:39,783 --> 00:08:45,399
cities used the stop-and-frisk power so heavily that it became the center of a
national argument

91
00:08:45,399 --> 00:08:51,016
about who gets stopped, and how often, and why .

92
00:08:51,016 --> 00:08:57,445
Picture how that plays out now. An officer does not need to watch you commit a
crime. He needs

93
00:08:57,445 --> 00:09:03,875
a handful of facts he can later put into words — where you were, what you did,
how it fit a

94
00:09:03,875 --> 00:09:10,304
pattern he has seen before. On a good day, that is careful police work
stopping a real threat

95
00:09:10,304 --> 00:09:16,734
before it happens. On a bad day, the same low bar can make being stopped feel
less like an

96
00:09:16,734 --> 00:09:23,163
event and more like weather .

97
00:09:23,163 --> 00:09:28,779
That argument is not really a disagreement about the 1968 ruling. The Court
was careful. It

98
00:09:28,779 --> 00:09:34,395
demanded specific facts, not vague feelings, and it limited the frisk to a
search for weapons.

99
00:09:34,395 --> 00:09:40,012
The problem is what happens when a careful rule meets the pressure of a quota,
a bad assumption,

100
00:09:40,012 --> 00:09:45,628
or a long day on a hard street.

101
00:09:45,628 --> 00:09:51,631
And so Terry leaves us with a permanent tension. We want officers to be able
to protect themselves

102
00:09:51,631 --> 00:09:57,635
in the seconds before they know who they are dealing with. We also do not want
suspicion alone

103
00:09:57,635 --> 00:10:03,638
to be enough to stop and handle anyone, anywhere. The line between those two
things is thin,

104
00:10:03,638 --> 00:10:09,641
and it is redrawn on sidewalks every single day.

105
00:10:09,641 --> 00:10:14,935
Terry v. Ohio answered a question about the street: how much can the police do
to your body,

106
00:10:14,935 --> 00:10:20,228
in public, on less than proof. The detective watched two men, named a real
suspicion, and the

107
00:10:20,228 --> 00:10:25,522
Court let the gun stand .

108
00:10:25,522 --> 00:10:31,331
But almost everything in that case depended on being out in the open — on a
man the officer

109
00:10:31,331 --> 00:10:37,141
could see, on a sidewalk anyone could walk down. The Fourth Amendment grew up
protecting physical

110
00:10:37,141 --> 00:10:42,951
things: your house, your pockets, the ground you stand on.

111
00:10:42,951 --> 00:10:49,729
So what happens when the police do not want what is in your pockets, but what
is on the device

112
00:10:49,729 --> 00:10:56,507
inside them? When the thing they reach for is the phone that holds your
messages, your photos,

113
00:10:56,507 --> 00:11:03,285
your whole life? The next time the Court faced that question, it had to decide
whether the

114
00:11:03,285 --> 00:11:10,063
rules built for pockets and coats could possibly fit a computer that fits in
your hand.

115
00:11:10,063 --> 00:11:12,000
That is next time.
